  "marks": 1,
  "readingTitle": "Misconception check",
  "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Believing decomposition can only ever be applied once to a problem.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> A sub-problem can be <strong>decomposed again</strong> if it is still too complex — decomposition can be applied more than once, breaking a problem down as many times as needed.</p>",
  "question": "A sub-problem is still too complicated to solve directly. What should a programmer do?",
