  "source": "learn",
  "type": "mcq",
  "marks": 1,
  "readingTitle": "Assigning and accessing elements",
  "reading": "<h4>Writing to, and reading from, an element</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>To <strong>assign</strong> a value to an element, write the array name with the index in square brackets on the left of an <code>=</code>: <code>scores[0] = 90</code>.</li>\n<li>To <strong>access</strong> (read) the value stored at an element, use the same square-bracket notation anywhere a value is needed — for example inside a <code>print</code> statement or a calculation.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"code-block\">array ages[4]\nages[0] = 15\nages[1] = 16\nages[2] = 15\nages[3] = 17\nprint(ages[1])            // 16\ntotal = ages[0] + ages[2]\nprint(total)               // 30</div>",
  "question": "For the array ages[4] set up above (ages[0]=15, ages[1]=16, ages[2]=15, ages[3]=17), what does  print(ages[1] + ages[3])  output?",
