  "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Thinking a compiled program still needs the compiler present to run.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Once a program has been <strong>compiled</strong>, the compiler has already done its job — translating the whole program into a standalone <strong>executable file</strong>. The compiler does <strong>not</strong> need to be present again for that executable to run. (It's an <strong>interpreter</strong> that must be present every time.)</p>",
  "question": "Does a user need the original compiler installed to run an already-compiled program?",
